Here's a C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file:
```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
int main() {
    std::string filename, word;
    int count = 0;
    std::cout << "Enter the filename: ";
    std::getline(std::cin, filename);
    std::cout << "Enter the word to search: ";
    std::getline(std::cin, word);
    std::ifstream file(filename);
    if (!file.is_open()) {
        std::cerr << "Error opening file " << filename << std::endl;
        return 1;
    }
    std::string line;
    while (std::getline(file, line)) {
        if (line.find(word) != std::string::npos) {
            count++;
        }
    }
    std::cout << "The word \"" << word << "\" occurs " << count << " times in the file." << std::endl;
    file.close();
    return 0;
}
```
Here's how the program works:
1. The program prompts the user to enter the filename and the word to search for.
2. The program opens the file in read mode using `std::ifstream`.
3. The program reads the file line by line using `std::getline`.
4. For each line, the program checks if the line contains the word using `line.find(word) != std::string::npos`.
